------------------------------------------------------------------------

# Tcells

The Total Tcells object is already processed and QCed, so we just load it and perform some basic preprocessing steps (normalization, variable features selection, scaling, PCA and UMAP) to be able to visualize it and subset CD4 Tcells.

```{r Load Tcells, cache.lazy = FALSE}
# Load Total Tcells
seu <- qread(seurat_path_Tcell_obj)

seu <- seu %>%
  NormalizeData() %>%
  FindVariableFeatures() %>%
  ScaleData(features = rownames(seu)) %>%
  RunPCA(features = VariableFeatures(.)) %>%
  RunUMAP(dims = 1:20)
cat("There is ", length(Cells(seu)),  " Tcells in the dataset.")

# Save qs object
qs::qsave(
  seu,
  file = file.path(
    DIR_DATA,
    "Processed_data",
    "seu_Tcells.qs")
)

# --- Cleanup: remove scale.data to save memory ---
DefaultAssay(seu) <- "RNA"
seu[["RNA"]]@scale.data <- matrix(0, 0, 0)  # removes scaled data
gc()  # forces garbage collection to free RAM
```

::: callout-important
Warning: The scale.data() slot consumes a substantial amount of memory and can significantly increase object size. In most workflows, it is not required, except for specific downstream analyses such as gene signature scoring or certain dimensionality reduction methods. To optimize memory usage and prevent unnecessary RAM overhead, it is recommended to remove the scale.data slot when not explicitly needed. It can be recomputed at any stage if required.
:::

We look at the size of the object and its different slots to see if we can optimize it by removing some slots that are not useful for our analysis. We can see that the scale.data slot is very large and we can remove it to save memory.

```{r Load raw data, cache.lazy = FALSE}
seu <- qs::qread(
  file.path(
    DIR_DATA,
    "Processed_data",
    "seu_Tcells.qs")
    # "seu_Tcells.rds")
)

cat("There is ", length(Cells(seu)),  " Tcells in the dataset.")
cat("The object have a size of ", format(object.size(seu), units = "GB"), ".\n")
cat("The RNA assay have a size of ", format(object.size(seu@assays$RNA), units = "GB"), ".\n")
cat("The ADT assay have a size of ", format(object.size(seu@assays$ADT), units = "GB"), ".\n")
cat("The metadata have a size of ", format(object.size(seu@meta.data), units = "GB"), ".\n")
cat("The data have a size of ", format(object.size(seu@assays$RNA@data), units = "GB"), ".\n")
format(object.size(seu@assays$RNA@counts), units = "GB")
format(object.size(seu@assays$RNA@scale.data), units = "GB")
lapply(seu@reductions, function(x) format(object.size(x), units = "GB") )
# List all major slots and size in GB
sizes <- sapply(slotNames(seu), function(sn) object.size(slot(seu, sn)))
sort(sizes, decreasing = TRUE)

DefaultAssay(seu) <- "RNA"
seu[["RNA"]]@scale.data <- matrix(0, 0, 0)  # supprime l’ancien scaled data
gc()  # force garbage collection pour libérer la RAM
```

Let's see the distribution of the ADT expression of CD4-TotalSeqB, which is a good marker of CD4 Tcells, to set a cutoff to separate CD8+ from CD4+ Tcells. We can also use the predicted.celltype.l1 annotation from previous abject done by PPA to help us to set this cutoff.

```{r Cutoff CD4 subset Viz}
VlnPlot(seu, 
        features = "CD4-TotalSeqB", 
        assay = "ADT", pt.size = 0, 
        group.by = "id") + 
  ggtitle("CD4-TotalSeqB (ADT)") +
  geom_hline(yintercept = 2, linetype = "dashed", color = "red")

VlnPlot(seu, 
        features = "CD4-TotalSeqB", 
        assay = "ADT", pt.size = 0, 
        group.by = "predicted.celltype.l1") + 
  ggtitle("CD4-TotalSeqB (ADT)") +
  geom_hline(yintercept = 2, linetype = "dashed", color = "red")

hist(seu@assays$ADT@data["CD4-TotalSeqB", ],
     breaks = 50,
     main = "Distribution of CD4-TotalSeqB (ADT) expression",
     xlab = "CD4-TotalSeqB (ADT) expression",
     ylab = "Frequency") 
abline(v = 2, lty = "dashed", col = "red")
```

We have a bimodal distribution of CD4-TotalSeqB ADT, so we can use it to set a cutoff to separate CD8+ from CD4+ Tcells.

------------------------------------------------------------------------

# CD4 Tcells {.tabset}

We will analyse CD4 Tcells separately from CD8 Tcells because they have different biology and we want to be able to identify specific subpopulations of CD4 Tcells that could be relevant in the context of HD vs MM.

## Subsetting {.tabset}

We will subset CD4 Tcells based on the ADT expression of CD4-TotalSeqB, which is a good marker of CD4 Tcells. We will set a cutoff at 2 which seems to separate well the two populations (CD4+ and CD4- Tcells) based on the distribution of the ADT expression and the predicted.celltype.l1 annotation.

Here set a treshold of 2 for the ADT expression of CD4-TotalSeqB to separate CD4+ from CD4- Tcells.

```{r Subset CD4+ cells}
#| cache: false


# Subset CD4 Tcells based on the ADT expression of CD4-TotalSeqB. We set a cutoff at 2 which seems to separate well the two populations (CD4+ and CD4- Tcells) based on the distribution of the ADT expression and the predicted.celltype.l1 annotation.
DefaultAssay(seu) <- "ADT"
seu$CD4_prot_pos <- seu@assays$ADT@data["CD4-TotalSeqB", ] > 2
cat("There is ", sum(seu$CD4_prot_pos), " CD4+ Tcells based on the ADT expression of CD4-TotalSeqB.\n")

Seurat::DefaultAssay(seu) <- "RNA"

seu_CD4 <- subset(
  seu,
  subset = CD4_prot_pos
)
```

Here we save the CD4 Tcells subset in a separate object to be able to perform QC and downstream analysis on this subset without having to load the whole dataset of Tcells which is very large and can be time consuming to load and process.

```{r Save CD4+ cells subset}
remove(seu)

# Save qs object
qs::qsave(
  seu_CD4,
  file = file.path(
    DIR_DATA,
    "Processed_data",
    "seu_CD4_Tcells.qs")
    # "seu_CD4_Tcells.rds")
)
```

