<!-- Ont voit donc l'effet de la maladie sur les programmes transcriptionnels dans les CD4 BCL6+ cells, et on peut voir quels programmes sont associés à la maladie (en rouge) ou à la santé (en bleu). On peut aussi voir les clusters de pathways qui partagent des gènes communs dans leurs leading edge, ce qui peut suggérer des processus biologiques liés. -->

<!-- Ici on repond à la question : "Chez les CD4 BCL6+, quels programmes transcriptionnels sont différents entre MM et HD ?" -->

<!-- ##### Compare BCL6+ vs BCL6- -->

<!-- On peut aussi comparer, pour une meme condition (HD ou MM), les programmes transcriptionnels entre les CD4 BCL6+ et les CD4 BCL6- pour voir l'effet de BCL6 sur les programmes transcriptionnels dans chaque condition. Ce sont des questions différentes, mais complémentaires pour comprendre le rôle de BCL6 dans les CD4 T cells dans le contexte de la maladie. -->

<!-- ###### In HD -->

<!-- ###### In MM -->

<!-- #### UCell {.tabset} -->

<!-- To developp and test if interesting signatures are enriched in specific clusters of CD4 T cells. For example, we can test if an IFN-gamma signature is enriched in a specific cluster of CD4 T cells, which could suggest that this cluster is involved in an IFN-gamma response. We can also test if an exhaustion signature is enriched in a specific cluster, which could suggest that this cluster is composed of exhausted CD4 T cells. UCell allows us to calculate module scores for these signatures at the single-cell level and visualize their distribution across clusters and conditions. -->

<!-- ```{r} -->

<!-- # library(UCell) -->

<!-- #  -->

<!-- # gene_sets <- list( -->

<!-- #   IFN_gamma = c("STAT1","IRF1","CXCL9","CXCL10"), -->

<!-- #   Exhaustion = c("PDCD1","LAG3","TIGIT","HAVCR2") -->

<!-- # ) -->

<!-- #  -->

<!-- # seu_CD4 <- AddModuleScore_UCell( -->

<!-- #   seu_CD4, -->

<!-- #   features = gene_sets -->

<!-- # ) -->

<!-- # VlnPlot(seu_CD4, features = "IFN_gamma_UCell", group.by = "condition") -->

<!-- ``` -->

<!-- #### SCENIC {.tabset} -->

<!-- To identify transcription factors (TFs) that are active in different clusters of CD4 T cells. GSEA only describe pathways, but not the TFs that regulate these pathways. SCENIC can help us identify which TFs are active in each cluster and how they might be regulating the observed transcriptional programs. SCENIC is more after GSEA (GSEA could also be run in annotation to identify cluster) -->

<!-- #### Trajectory inference -->

<!-- Maybe for this project but for future projects, trajectory inference can be used to identify potential differentiation trajectories of CD4 T cells and how they might differ between conditions. For example, we could identify a trajectory of CD4 T cell differentiation from naive to effector to exhausted states, and see if the distribution of cells along this trajectory differs between MM and HD. -->

<!-- #### InferCNV -->

<!-- Maybe for future projects, inferCNV can be used to identify potential copy number variations (CNVs) in the CD4 T cells, which could be associated with the disease state. For example, we could identify CNVs that are enriched in CD4 T cells from MM patients compared to HD, which could suggest a role for these CNVs in the disease process. -->

